## 4. Data Visualization (ggplot2)
Always apply the following theme. **Note: Legend titles must be removed.**

```r
theme_custom <- function(base_size = 14) {
  theme_minimal(base_size = base_size) +
    theme(
      plot.title       = element_text(face = "bold", color = "#012169"),
      legend.position  = "bottom",
      legend.title     = element_blank(),
      plot.background  = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
      panel.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA)
    )
}
```

## 5. Export Standards (figures & tables)
- All rendered outputs (figures and tables) must be written to the `docs/` subfolders of the project so they can be tracked and versioned.

### 5.1 Figures (ggplot2 / `ggsave`)

- All figures generated must be saved in the `docs/figures/` directory (GitHub Pages) and follow the naming convention below.
- Location: Always write figure output files to `docs/figures/`.
- Naming: Append a date-time suffix in the form `YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS` (e.g., `filename_20260302_153045.png`). This requirement applies to all figure files created by the project.
- Format: Always set `bg = "transparent"` and provide explicit `width` and `height` dimensions.
- Execution: Wrap `ggsave()` (and any other figure export) calls in a check on `save_figures`, e.g., `if (isTRUE(save_figures)) { ... }`.

Standard `ggsave()` template:

```r
# Logical flag to control whether figures are written to disk
save_figures <- TRUE

# Generate date-time suffix
dat_suffix <- format(Sys.time(), "%Y%m%d_%H%M%S")

# Example conditional save
if (isTRUE(save_figures)) {
  ggsave(
    filename = here::here("docs", "figures", paste0("plot_name_", dat_suffix, ".png")),
    plot = last_plot(),
    width = 8, 
    height = 6, 
    bg = "transparent"
  )
}
```

### 5.2 Tables (LaTeX `.tex`)

- All publication-quality tables (e.g., regression output, summary statistics) must be saved as LaTeX `.tex` files in the `docs/tables/` directory.
- Location: Always write table output files to `docs/tables/`.
- Naming: Append a date-time suffix in the form `YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS` (e.g., `table_name_20260302_153045.tex`). This requirement applies to all table files created by the project.
- Summary statistics tables should, by default, be created using the `summary_stats_function` defined in the shared utilities script at `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/dratnadiwakara/r-utilities/refs/heads/main/summary_stat_tables.R`, imported via `source("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/dratnadiwakara/r-utilities/refs/heads/main/summary_stat_tables.R")`, and the resulting tables must be exported to LaTeX `.tex` files following the same naming, location, and date-suffix conventions as other tables.
- Global table export toggle: Define a single logical flag `save_tables <- TRUE` in any script or `.qmd` that can export tables. No table should be written unless `save_tables` is `TRUE`.
- Local per-table toggle: For each individual table, define a local logical indicator (e.g., `export_this_table <- TRUE`) so that specific tables can be skipped even when `save_tables` is `TRUE`.
- Execution pattern: Wrap each table export call in a combined check on the global and local flags, for example:

```r
save_tables <- TRUE      # Global toggle
export_this_table <- TRUE # Local toggle for this table

dat_suffix <- format(Sys.time(), "%Y%m%d_%H%M%S")

if (isTRUE(save_tables) && isTRUE(export_this_table)) {
  writeLines(
    table_tex,  # character vector containing LaTeX code for the table
    con = here::here("docs", "tables", paste0("table_name_", dat_suffix, ".tex"))
  )
}
```

## 6. Econometric Modeling (fixest)
Always use the `fixest` package for regressions. Use global macros (`setFixest_fml` and `setFixest_etable`) to maintain a clean and consistent model structure across scripts.

### Macro Structure Template
Initialize scripts using this order (adjusting the specific variables based on the unit of analysis, this is only an example.):

```r
library(fixest)

# Template: Adjust geography/controls based on the specific Task
setFixest_fml(
  ..fe       = ~ ZIPBR + cbsa_yr,                        # Unit + Time Fixed Effects
  ..controls = ~ zip_growth_3yr + log1p(branches_zip_lag1), # Standard Controls
  ..het_vars = ~ sophisticated + factor_age_bin + log_income # Heterogeneity/Interaction terms
)

# Global Export Formatting 
setFixest_etable(
  signif.code = c("***" = 0.01, "**" = 0.05, "*" = 0.1),
  se.below = TRUE
)
```

### 6.1 Table labeling and row ordering (`etable`)

- **Human-readable labels:** Always pass a `dict =` argument to `fixest::etable()` so that row labels are human-readable (e.g., `"log(family_income)"` → `"log(Family Income)"`).
- **Ordering by labels, not variable names:** When using the `order =` argument in `etable()`, specify the desired row order using the **printed labels**, not the underlying variable names. For example, if the label is `"log(Family Income)"`, the `order` vector should contain `"Family Income"` (the underlying economic quantity) rather than `"log(family_income)"`.
- **Intercept placement:** Ensure the intercept row is labeled `"Constant"` (via `dict = c(covariate_labels, "(Intercept)" = "Constant")`) and appears **last** in the table by including `"Constant"` as the final entry in the `order` vector.
- **Consistency across outputs:** Use the **same label-based `order` vector** for both on-screen (`html`) and LaTeX (`tex = TRUE`) versions of the table so row ordering is identical in all exported outputs.

## 7. Script Organization & Quarto Analysis

### 7.1 Script locations

- **Sample construction scripts (`.R`):**
  - All sample construction and data preparation scripts must live in `code/sample-construction/`.
  - These scripts must be plain R scripts with the `.R` extension.
  - Their primary responsibilities are to read raw or external data, perform cleaning and sample construction, and write processed outputs into the `data/` folder (following the Data Management rules above).

- **Analysis scripts (`.qmd`):**
  - All empirical analysis and result-generation scripts must live in `code/result-generation/`.
  - These scripts must be Quarto documents with the `.qmd` extension.
  - `.qmd` files in `code/result-generation/` are the canonical entry points for running analyses and producing tables and figures.

### 7.2 Structure of `.qmd` analysis files

- **Document type:**
  - All `.qmd` analysis files must use `type: source` in the document front matter (not `type: notebook`).

- **Task-per-chunk structure:**
  - Each logically distinct task (e.g., loading data, computing summary statistics, estimating regressions, generating a specific figure or table) should be placed in its own code chunk.
  - Large monolithic chunks should be split into smaller, clearly labeled chunks to improve reproducibility, readability, and debugging.

- **Narrative vs. code:**
  - Each figure or table should be preceded by a heading and a journal-style description (one or two paragraphs) that states what the exhibit presents, the sample and unit of observation, the dependent variable (LHS), key right-hand side variables (RHS), and what each column or column group represents. Do not interpret coefficients or findings in these descriptions; keep them descriptive only.
  - Each other important chunk should be preceded by a short sentence or heading describing its purpose (e.g., "Estimate baseline regressions" or "Construct event-study plot").
  - Inside code chunks, comments should still be used sparingly to explain non-obvious implementation details, assumptions, or tricky logic, consistent with the guideline to comment the **WHY**, not the **WHAT**.

### 7.3 Execution options and output cleanliness

- **Suppress warnings and messages by default:**
  - All `.qmd` analysis files must suppress warnings and messages by default by setting `warning: false` and `message: false` in the document-level `execute:` block in the front matter.
  - Chunk-level overrides are allowed when a specific warning or message is genuinely informative and should appear in the rendered document.

- **Example minimal front matter for analysis files:**

```yaml
---
title: "Analysis Title"
format: html
type: source
execute:
  warning: false
  message: false
---
```

## 8. Results Storage & Model Management
To ensure models are easily exportable to tables, follow this list-based storage pattern:

- **Initialization:** Always start the analysis section with `r <- list()`.
- **Naming:** Use descriptive keys for the list (e.g., `"Joint"`, `"Pre 2012"`, `"Het Post 2012"`).
- **Interaction Syntax:** Use the shorthand `formula = y ~ var1*(..het_vars)` for heterogeneity analysis to maintain consistency.
- **VCOV:** Default to clustering at the unit level (e.g., `vcov = ~ZIPBR` or `vcov = ~RSSDID`) as specified in the plan.

**Pattern Example:**
```r
r <- list()

# Use macros and list storage
r[["Joint"]] <- feols(
  gr_1yr ~ share_deps_closed + pred_share_opened + ..controls | ..fe,
  data = dt_combined, 
  vcov = ~ZIPBR
)

# Interaction with heterogeneity macros
r[["Het Pre 2012"]] <- feols(
  gr_1yr ~ share_deps_closed*(..het_vars) + pred_share_opened*(..het_vars) + ..controls | ..fe,
  data = dt_combined[YEAR <= 2012], 
  vcov = ~ZIPBR
)
```

